Fix __host__/__device__ math-function ambiguities in catboost CUDA kernels.

CUDA 12.x's nvcc (with newer libcudacxx) restricts which standard-math
overloads are callable from __device__ code. Bare calls like

    pow(float, float)
    ceil(float)
    log(float)
    log2(float)
    sqrt(float)
    abs(float)

resolve to the host-only overload set, producing diagnostics of the form:

    error: calling a __host__ function("X(float)") from a __device__ function

CUDA's runtime math header provides explicit *f-suffixed overloads
(powf, ceilf, logf, log2f, sqrtf, fabsf) that ARE __device__-callable. The
fix is mechanical: replace the bare call with the *f-suffixed overload when
the argument(s) are float. We leave bare-double / bare-int calls alone --
only the bare-float forms are broken.

Audited every catboost/cuda/**/*.{cu,cuh} call to bare pow/ceil/log/log2/
sqrt/abs and patched the ones where the argument resolves to float.

diff --git a/catboost/cuda/cuda_util/kernel/kernel_helpers.cuh b/catboost/cuda/cuda_util/kernel/kernel_helpers.cuh
--- a/catboost/cuda/cuda_util/kernel/kernel_helpers.cuh
+++ b/catboost/cuda/cuda_util/kernel/kernel_helpers.cuh
@@ -220,7 +220,7 @@ namespace NKernel {
 
     __forceinline__ __device__ uint2 GetPair(ui32 idx) {
         uint2 pair;
-        pair.y = ui32((1.0f + sqrt(8.0f * idx + 1.0f)) * 0.5f);
+        pair.y = ui32((1.0f + sqrtf(8.0f * idx + 1.0f)) * 0.5f);
         pair.x = idx - ((pair.y * (pair.y - 1)) >> 1);
         return pair;
     }
